recalls.Component: AIR BAGS: AIR BAG/RESTRAINT CONTROL MODULE
recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2016-2017 911 and Boxster, 2016 Cayman and Panamera vehicles.  The air bag Electronic Control Unit (ECU) may have a defective power supply capacitor that can result in air bag deactivation or inadvertent deployment of the air bags.
recalls.Consequence: Deactivated air bags increase the risk of injury.  Inadvertent deployment of the air bags increase the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will install new software and replace the air bag ECU as necessary, free of charge.   Interim notices informing owners of the safety risk were mailed September 13, 2019.  Owners received a second notice and the recall began February 12, 2020.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AKB4.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain model year 2017 718 Boxster, 718 Boxster S, 718 Cayman, 718 Cayman S, 911 Carrera, 911 Carrera S, 911 Carrera S Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4S, 911 Turbo, 911 Turbo S, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, and 911 Turbo Cabriolet vehicles.  The seat mounted side air bag inflator initiator may fail to ignite during a crash.
recalls.Consequence: If the air bag inflator initiator fails to ignite, the side air bag will not deploy, increasing the risk of injury in the event of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will replace the affected air bag modules, free of charge.  The recall began April 2017.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AG10.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2017 911 Carrera Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4 Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, 911 Carrera S Cabriolet, 911 Targa S, 911 Targa 4S, 911 Turbo Cabriolet, 718 Boxter and 718 Boxter S vehicles.  During manufacturing, the windshield may not have been properly bonded to the vehicle, allowing it to detach in a crash.  As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (FMVSS) number 212, "Windshield Mounting."
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a crash, if the windshield separates from the vehicle, it can increase the risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will rebond the windshield, free of charge.  The recall began on May 12, 2016.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for the recall is AH04.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: Engine Connecting Rod Bearing Failure
issues.description: The 4.0L naturally aspirated engine in the 991.2 GT3 has experienced connecting rod bearing failures, particularly on engines that have been tracked extensively or driven aggressively. This can lead to catastrophic engine damage and complete engine replacement.
issues.fix_description: Complete engine rebuild or replacement with updated bearings and proper break-in procedure
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, proper engine warm-up, avoid aggressive driving during break-in period, frequent oil analysis

issues.title: Magnesium Wheel Corrosion
issues.description: The optional magnesium wheels are prone to corrosion and cracking, especially when exposed to road salt or harsh weather conditions. This affects both appearance and structural integrity of the wheels.
issues.fix_description: Replace affected wheels with aluminum alternatives or new magnesium wheels
issues.prevention: Regular wheel cleaning, avoid road salt exposure, proper storage in winter

issues.title: PDK Transmission Software Issues
issues.description: Early production models experienced PDK transmission software calibration issues causing harsh shifts, delayed engagement, and inconsistent performance in track mode.
issues.fix_description: Software update at authorized Porsche dealer
issues.prevention: Regular software updates during scheduled maintenance

issues.title: Front Splitter Cracking and Damage
issues.description: The carbon fiber front splitter is prone to cracking and damage from road debris, curb strikes, and normal driving conditions due to its low ground clearance and exposed position.
issues.fix_description: Replace damaged carbon fiber splitter with OEM or aftermarket unit
issues.prevention: Careful driving over speed bumps, avoid steep driveways, use front lift system if equipped

issues.title: Rear Wing Actuator Motor Failure
issues.description: The electric motor that controls the rear wing position can fail, causing the wing to become stuck in one position or lose automatic adjustment functionality.
symptoms: Wing not responding to speed changes
issues.fix_description: Replace wing actuator motor and recalibrate system
issues.prevention: Regular operation through full range of motion, keep wing mechanism clean

issues.title: Carbon Ceramic Brake Disc Premature Wear
issues.description: Carbon ceramic brake discs showing premature wear patterns, cracking, or delamination, particularly on track-driven vehicles or those subjected to heavy braking.
issues.fix_description: Replace carbon ceramic brake discs and pads as a set
issues.prevention: Proper brake cooling periods, avoid excessive heat cycling, use appropriate brake pads for intended use

issues.title: Oil Cooler Line Leakage
issues.description: Oil cooler lines can develop leaks at connection points or along the line itself, leading to oil loss and potential engine damage if not addressed promptly.
symptoms: Visible oil stains on cooler lines
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty oil cooler lines and fittings, check entire cooling system
issues.prevention: Regular inspection during oil changes, proper torque specifications during maintenance

issues.title: Interior Carbon Fiber Trim Delamination
issues.description: Carbon fiber interior trim pieces can experience delamination or bubbling of the clear coat, affecting the appearance and potentially leading to further deterioration.
issues.fix_description: Replace affected trim pieces or professional refinishing
issues.prevention: Avoid harsh chemicals, use appropriate cleaning products, minimize UV exposure

issues.title: Track Mode Overheating Issues
issues.description: Some vehicles experience overheating during extended track sessions, with cooling system unable to maintain optimal temperatures under sustained high-performance driving.
issues.fix_description: Upgrade cooling system components, check radiator efficiency, ensure proper airflow
issues.prevention: Monitor temperatures during track use, take cooling breaks, maintain cooling system properly

issues.title: Fuel System Vapor Lock
issues.description: In hot weather conditions, especially during track use, the fuel system can experience vapor lock causing fuel starvation and engine performance issues.
symptoms: Loss of power at high RPM
issues.fix_description: Upgrade fuel system components, improve fuel cooling, check fuel pump operation
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, avoid extended high-temperature operation, maintain fuel system

editorial.tagline: Pure naturally aspirated perfection meets track-bred precision
editorial.hero_blurb: The 991.2 GT3 represents the pinnacle of naturally aspirated engineering in the modern era. With its screaming 4.0-liter flat-six and razor-sharp chassis dynamics, this is a love letter to analog driving enthusiasts.
editorial.essence: This is the last great naturally aspirated 911 GT3, delivering 500hp of pure, linear power without turbocharged assistance. Every component exists to serve the driving experience, creating an unfiltered connection between driver and machine that modern sports cars rarely achieve.
editorial.heritage: Building on decades of GT3 evolution, the 991.2 generation refined the formula established by the legendary 996 GT3. This iteration perfected the balance between track capability and road usability while maintaining the philosophical purity that makes GT3s special.
editorial.design_philosophy: Function follows form in every detail, from the aggressive aerodynamic package to the stripped-down interior. Porsche's engineers prioritized weight reduction, aerodynamic efficiency, and driver engagement over luxury amenities.
editorial.motorsport_history: Direct descendant of Porsche's GT3 Cup and RSR racing programs, sharing DNA with cars that dominate endurance racing worldwide. The road car benefits from decades of motorsport development and continuous track testing.
editorial.engine_character: The 4.0-liter flat-six is an absolute masterpiece - linear power delivery builds progressively to a spine-tingling 9,000rpm redline. No turbo lag, no artificial enhancement, just pure mechanical symphony that rewards high-rpm exploration.
editorial.transmission_feel: The PDK gearbox delivers lightning-fast shifts with surgical precision, while the available manual transmission offers pure mechanical engagement for purists. Both options perfectly complement the engine's high-rev character.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Surgically precise and utterly predictable, the chassis communicates every detail of the road surface. The rear-wheel steering system enhances both low-speed agility and high-speed stability without compromising the classic 911 feel.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulically-assisted rack provides unfiltered feedback with perfectly weighted resistance. Every input translates directly to the front wheels with zero ambiguity - this is how steering should feel in a sports car.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive carbon-ceramic discs provide fade-free stopping power with incredible modulation. The pedal feel is firm and progressive, inspiring complete confidence whether on track or mountain roads.
editorial.sound_signature: An intoxicating mechanical symphony that builds from a purposeful idle to a race-car wail at 9,000rpm. The flat-six's distinctive growl combined with intake honk creates an addictive acoustic experience.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who appreciate naturally aspirated engines and don't mind sacrificing comfort for performance. Perfect for enthusiasts who regularly attend track days or simply want the most engaging street driving experience possible.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Daily commuters seeking luxury amenities, buyers prioritizing straight-line speed over handling finesse, or those uncomfortable with firm suspension and road noise.
editorial.buyers_summary: This represents the end of an era - likely the last naturally aspirated GT3 we'll see. Find the cleanest, lowest-mileage example possible, as these will only become more valuable and harder to find.

expertReviews.title: Why the 991.2 is a great Porsche 911 GT3 *one take*
pros: 4L naturally aspirated engine with 9000 RPM capability
PDK gearbox suits the engine perfectly
Track-ready with ceramics, cage, and 918 bucket seats
Clean analog dashboard with 5 clocks
Excellent value at current pricing
Great balance of aggression and beauty
Outstanding performance while remaining drivable on road
Motorsport-oriented in truest GT3 form
cons: Won't reach 9000 RPM redline on public roads
Less rare than Touring version
More digitized than ideal for some preferences
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 represents the GT3 in its most pure form - a road-legal track car that excels at both. With its celebrated 4L naturally aspirated engine, clinical PDK transmission, and motorsport-focused setup, it delivers outstanding performance while remaining enjoyable on public roads. At current pricing around Â£125k, it offers great value compared to the rare Touring versions, and represents a significant piece of the Andreas Preuninger era. The reviewer considers it the best-looking GT3 generation and praises its perfect balance of performance and usability.

expertReviews.title: How the Porsche 911 GT3 (991.2) came close to perfection
pros: Improved electric steering with much better feel than early 991s
4.0L naturally aspirated flat-six engine with 9,000 RPM redline and incredible sound
Significantly improved aerodynamics with 20% more downforce and no drag penalty
PDK gearbox suits the motorsport-focused character perfectly
Excellent ride quality that filters harsh impacts while preserving road feel
Nearly identical performance to newer 992 GT3 at lower price point
cons: Electric steering still not quite as good as hydraulic systems of old
Large footprint compared to earlier 911 generations
PDK-only option may disappoint manual transmission purists
Still commands premium pricing in used market
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 represents Porsche's successful refinement of a controversial generation. Through hundreds of small improvements, particularly to the steering software and aerodynamics, plus the addition of the sublime 4.0L engine, Porsche transformed the GT3 into what Andreas Preuninger called 'one step closer to perfection.' The reviewer suggests this generation offers nearly identical performance to the newer 992 while being more accessible, making it an exceptional sports car that excels at everything it does.

expertReviews.title: Driving the Porsche 911 GT3 991.2 | Review, Sound, and ... by Classic Car Club Manhattan
pros: Exceptional steering precision and directness
Impressive electronic suspension balances communication with comfort
PDK gearbox perfectly matched to engine and performance
Highly communicative driving experience with excellent road feel
Comfortable one-piece carbon seats suitable for long drives
500hp 4L flat-6 engine revs to 9,000 RPM with incredible throttle response
Perfect balance of confidence-inspiring grip with just enough danger to be exciting
cons: Requires constant attention and restraint due to extreme performance capability
Can reach dangerous speeds very quickly
Limited adjustability in one-piece carbon seats
Paddle shifters move with steering wheel rather than staying fixed
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 represents the sweet spot of modern GT3s - offering race car-like performance and communication while remaining civilized enough for road use. With its 500hp engine, precise handling, and excellent PDK transmission, it delivers an exceptional driving experience that requires respect and skill to fully appreciate. The reviewer emphasizes it's closest thing to a race car you can drive on the road, but warns it demands complete attention and restraint due to its incredible performance capabilities.

expertReviews.title: Why is THIS GT3 the best of all generations? | 9k RPM ...
pros: Exceptional manual gearbox with short throws and precise feel
Outstanding naturally aspirated 4.0L engine sound up to 9k RPM
Superior handling compared to Ferrari 458, Huracan, McLaren 570
Perfect balance between analog feel and modern technology
Track-capable yet comfortable for daily driving
Bulletproof reliability
Rear wheel steering enhances stability
cons: Price point at nearly $200,000
Newer 992 GT3 has digital tachometer vs analog
Manual transmission may not suit all drivers
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 represents the perfect GT3 generation - combining the return of the manual transmission option with a screaming 4.0L naturally aspirated engine, exceptional handling that surpasses supercars costing similar money, and the ideal balance of analog driving feel with modern assistance features. The reviewer considers it superior to newer 992 models due to its analog tachometer and calls it potentially the greatest daily driver supercar.

expertReviews.title: Porsche 911 GT3: Full Road Review - Carfection
pros: Exceptional steering feel and feedback
Brilliant 4.0L naturally aspirated engine with 500hp that revs to 9000rpm
Outstanding manual gearbox that's engaging at all speeds
Excellent ride quality and suspension setup
Strong chassis balance and traction
Involving and rewarding to drive at any speed
Feels compact and wieldy despite being a 991
cons: Roll cage reduces practicality
Some may prefer the subtler Touring version without the wing
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 is described as fabulous and brilliant - a car that's hard not to recommend. The reviewer considers it his lottery winner car choice again after the 991 gen 1 lost that status. It excels at all speeds with exceptional steering, a magnificent naturally aspirated engine, and outstanding manual transmission. The car manages to be both track-focused and road-usable with excellent ride quality. Compared to the GT3 RS, the standard GT3 with manual transmission left a greater impression on the reviewer.

expertReviews.title: What It's Like To Own A 991.2 Porsche 911 GT3!!
pros: 4L naturally aspirated flat-6 engine
9,000 RPM redline capability
Six-speed manual transmission option
Comfortable carbon bucket seats
Excellent Apple CarPlay integration
Great speakers and interior quality
Strong Porsche community
Front lift system works quickly
Cup 2 tires provide good grip
Rev matching downshifts
cons: Less grippy front end compared to McLaren 570S
Noticeable body roll especially in S-curves
Steering feels less communicative than McLaren
Very loud carbon ceramic brakes
High purchase price ($180-200k)
Base headlights instead of PDLS Plus
Requires more driver skill to extract performance
expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT3 is an excellent sports car that delivers a pure driving experience with its naturally aspirated engine and manual transmission, but the owner found it disappointing compared to his previous McLaren 570S. While praising its comfort, interior quality, and community, he noted handling limitations including body roll and less confident front-end grip. Despite not regretting the purchase, he's considering selling for a McLaren 600LT, suggesting the GT3 didn't meet his elevated expectations after 3 years of anticipation.
